Most Spark "performance issues" aren't really about Spark. They're about misreading the UI, caching things you shouldn't, broadcasting things that shouldn't be broadcast, and ignoring the AQE/DPP defaults that changed in 4.x.

I sat down and wrote every Spark mistake I've watched break production. Mine, my team's, and the ones people screamed about.

It turned into a checklist:
- Partitioning that doesn't fight you (coalesce vs repartition vs bucketing)
- When caching is slower than recomputing
- Memory layout, overhead, and why your "8G executor" actually wants 12G
- Joins that explode (broadcast, skew, bucket)
- JDBC reads that are silently single-threaded
- The Spark 4.x defaults you probably haven't turned on yet
- What to actually look at in the UI before you start guessing

Every item came from a real production screwup.